    ROOT CAUSE                                                                  
    bc/storage.c line 176 contains the function more_arrays() which expands     
    the program’s name/array storage.                                           
    The loop that initializes the newly‑expanded slots is written as            
                                                                                
                                                                                
     for (; indx < v_count; indx++)      /* ← bug */                            
         arrays[indx] = NULL;                                                   
                                                                                
                                                                                
    v_count is a different counter that can be larger than the newly‑allocated  
    capacity a_count.                                                           
    When the input program defines more identifiers than the current capacity   
    (v_count > a_count), the loop overruns the freshly‑reallocated arrays       
    buffer, writes past the heap block and corrupts adjacent heap metadata.     
    When later code invokes find_id() (frame 0) or lookup() (frame 1) it        
    dereferences a corrupted id_rec pointer, causing the observed               
    EXC_BAD_ACCESS crash.                                                       
                                                                                
    In short, the defect is an off‑by‑one / capacity‑misuse bug that writes     
    past the allocated storage, leading to heap corruption and a later crash.   
                                                                                
    --------------------------------------------------------------------------  
                                                                                
    LOCAL FIX (minimal change that stops the immediate crash)                   
                                                                                
    Replace the erroneous loop limit v_count with the actual allocated          
    capacity a_count:                                                           
                                                                                
                                                                                
              /* Initialize the new elements. */                                
     -        for (; indx < v_count; indx++)                                    
     +        for (; indx < a_count; indx++)                                    
                  arrays[indx] = NULL;                                          
                                                                                
                                                                                
    If a project prefers to keep the original intent of initializing only a     
    known number of slots, the safer pattern is:                                
                                                                                
                                                                                
     for (; indx < a_count && indx < v_count; indx++)                           
         arrays[indx] = NULL;                                                   
                                                                                
                                                                                
    This change guarantees that the write never exceeds the bounds of the       
    memory that was just allocated.                                             
                                                                                
    --------------------------------------------------------------------------  
                                                                                
    GLOBAL FIX (preventing this whole class of bugs)                            
                                                                                
     1 Enforce a strict capacity invariant – keep a separate constant (MAX_V)   
       or validate that the caller respects v_count <= a_count.  Add an         
       explicit check in the call site:                                         
                                                                                
        assert(v_count <= a_count);                                             
                                                                                
     2 Introduce a bounded container – replace the raw char **a_names and       
       bc_var_array **arrays with a struct that carries its length, e.g.:       
                                                                                
        typedef struct {                                                        
            char  **names;                                                      
            bc_var_array **vec;                                                 
            size_t  size;      /* actual number of used slots */                
            size_t  capacity;  /* allocated slots */                            
        } name_store;                                                           
                                                                                
       All accesses go through accessor functions that perform bounds checks.   
     3 Use safe allocation helpers – encapsulate the growth logic in a          
       function that computes the new capacity as MAX(old_count + STORE_INCR,   
       MIN_REQUIRED) and returns an error if the requested size would overflow  
       size_t.  This eliminates accidental overflow of the size calculation.    
     4 Static analysis / sanitizers – enable compiler‑time warnings             
       (-Warray-bounds, -D_FORTIFY_SOURCE=2) and runtime address‑sanitizer      
       checks in the build configuration.  These would have flagged the         
       v_count misuse automatically.                                            
     5 Testing policy – add unit tests that feed inputs generating larger       
       v_count values than the current capacity, ensuring the growth routine    
       never overruns.                                                          
                                                                                
    These structural changes ensure that any future growth of the name/array    
    buffers is always performed within the allocated bounds, eliminating        
    heap‑overflow vulnerabilities that previously manifested as crashes inside  
    lookups.                                                                    
                                                                                
